## 6. Security Design Explanation

The security policy design follows a risk-based access control model.

Users coming from trusted networks receive access with MFA and longer session lifetimes. Users coming from untrusted networks are still allowed access, but their sessions are shorter and MFA is required at every sign-in.

This improves security by reducing the chance of unauthorized access from risky locations while still allowing legitimate users to work.

---

## 7. Key Security Decisions

| Decision | Reason |
|---|---|
| MFA required for both trusted and untrusted networks | Protects all sign-ins |
| Shorter session for untrusted network | Reduces risk if a session is compromised |
| Persistent browser sessions disabled | Prevents long-term saved sessions |
| Okta Verify required for high-security groups | Stronger authentication method |
| Separate network zones created | Allows policy rules to evaluate access by location |

---

## 8. Final Result

The Okta security policy configuration successfully enforces:

- MFA for users in the CyberOps group.
- Different session lifetimes based on network trust.
- Stronger authenticator enrollment for Finance and Help Support groups.
- Network-based security rules using Okta zones.

